Pt. 5, 5935 ft, Gen. Hitchcock Camping Area.  Mixed pine-oak-cypress woodland in deep canyon.

I'm a little unclear about the taxonomy for this shrubby cherry.  This looks basically like all the black cherry shrubs and trees further east.  In Pima County, both ITIS and the USDA PLANTS database show only Prunus serotina var. rufula, with P. s. var. virens occurring in adjacent counties.  Those sources also call this "Black Cherry", with ITIS adding the common name "Southwestern Chokecherry" for it.  ITIS uses "Western Chokecherry" for P. virginiana var. demissa.

Images of some of the other dominant woody species at this site were uploaded from the previous day:
http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/3081194
http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/3080835
http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/3081201

An explanation of this elevational transect can be found with this observation:
http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/3090533

description: Árbol de follaje ligero, a menudo plantado y conservado en campos de cultivo, orillas de caminos y en jardines. Las flores son libadas por insectos, entre ellos abejas domésticas (Apis mellifera). Los frutos maduros son comestibles, sabrosos, y son consumidos por aves silvestres como mirlas (Turdus fuscater), clarineros (Anisognathus igniventris), cotingas (Ampelion rubrocristatus), cardenales (Piranga rubra) y azulejos (Thraupis episcopus). Las gruesas semillas tardan bastante en germinar y las plántulas pueden crecer algún tiempo a la sombra de otros árboles. Sin embargo, a la larga necesitan exposición directa al sol para un adecuado desarrollo.

Associated canopy species in order of abundance: Acer saccharum, Fraxinus americana, Tilia americana, and Prunus serotina. 

Understory species were sparse, but included A. saccharum, and Ostrya virginiana, while the groundcover was dominated by Poa nemoralis, Solidago spp., A. saccharum seedlings, and Carex spp. 

The site appeared to have experienced historical disturbance from livestock grazing, and more recently from decline and death of F. americana.
